    <section id="main" class="wrapper">
      <div class="inner">
        <header class="major">
          <h2>Artefact: Critique of the Grandfather–Father–Son (GFS) Backup Procedure</h2>
          <p>critical evaluation</p>
        </header>

        <section>
          <h3>Overview</h3>
          <p>This artefact briefly evaluates the GFS backup rotation (daily/weekly/monthly) with emphasis on storage efficiency for large databases and comparative effectiveness versus alternative backup strategies.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h3>Critical Evaluation</h3>
          <p>
            The Grandfather–Father–Son (GFS) backup procedure is a tiered rotation system that cycles daily, weekly, and 
            monthly backups to balance retention and resource efficiency. By re-using media within structured intervals, 
            GFS minimises redundant full backups and reduces storage load, which is critical when handling large databases. 
            This incremental approach parallels the principles of efficient data wrangling described by McKinney (2022), 
            where controlled redundancy and clear versioning maintain data integrity while limiting resource overhead. 
            Similarly, Cove (2024) highlights the value of systematic data management for scalable analytics — a concept 
            echoed in GFS’s orderly retention hierarchy. Compared with continuous or full-mirror backups, GFS offers a 
            cost-effective and operationally stable method, though recovery granularity may be coarser. Overall, GFS remains 
            an effective strategy when balanced with modern automation and off-site replication.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h3>Reflection</h3>
          <p>This task strengthened my ability to relate classical IT resilience patterns to data-science workflows: controlled redundancy, verifiable checkpoints, and cost-aware retention. I will prioritise rotation policies, routine restore tests, and clear retention schedules when designing future data pipelines.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h3>References</h3>
          <ul>
